<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Scottish Public Health Network and the Scottish Welfare Reform Health Impact Delivery Group</title></head><body><div><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Scottish Public Health Network</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> and NHS Health Scotland</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This evidence from the Scottish Public Health Network and NHS Health Scotland focuses on the health impact of the social size criteria in Scotland.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In Scotland, 82,500 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">households </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are effected by the social size criteria, of whom 68,500 are under occupyin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">g by one bedroom.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">However each year on average only 20,000 one bedroom properties become available for rent in the social housing sector. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Around 80% of households affected by the under-occupancy penalty i.e. around 63,500 households </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Scotland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">estimated to contain an adult with a disability recognised under the Disability Discrimination Act</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This evidence </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">examines the impact of debt on health and explains how debt can have a negative impact on both physical and mental health.  It also explains</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that people with mental health conditions are more likely to be effected by debt when compared with the general population.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The evidence goes onto explore the impact of homelessness on health, identifying an increase in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">chronic </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">health </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">conditions as well</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> as anxiety, stress, self-harm, other mental health problems and infectious diseases</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  It also explains that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">children in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">temporary accommodation are more likely to experience</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> behavioural disturbance, have higher levels of illness and infection, have poor s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">leep patterns and are more prone to accidental injury</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The impact of low income on health is also explored, concluding that the impact of the social size criteria is likely to increase both income inequalities and health inequalities in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Scotland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, as well</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> as increase fuel poverty and food poverty resulting in a number of negative health outcomes.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Finally, the evidence summarises the impact of Discretionary Housing Payments on primary care in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Scotland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">; t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">additional work of providing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">medical </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">evidence fo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">r DHP applications falls disproportionately on general practices in areas of deprivation in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Scotland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> which are already struggling as a result of the inverse care law</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Introduction</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35pt; text-indent:-35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.1 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The Scottish Public Health Network (ScotP</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">HN</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and NHS Health Scotland </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">welcome this opportunity to provide information for the Work and Pensions Committee on the provision of support to meet housing costs in the reformed welfare system.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35pt; text-indent:-35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">This submission will focus on the health impact of the social size criteria and the impact on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">health and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NHS services in Scotland.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  The submission has </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">six</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">distinct sections </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">focusing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on social size criteria</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">section one provides background information on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ose submitting this information</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">section two summarises </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the impact </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">on social sector housing in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> Scotland</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">section t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hree</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> summarise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the impact o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f debt, caused by rent arrears, on health</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">section </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">four</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> summarises the impact of homelessness on health</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">section five </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sum</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">arises the impact of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">low </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">income on health</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">section </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">six</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> summarises the impact of D</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">iscretionary Housing Payment</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> on NHS services</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35pt; text-indent:-35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ScotPHN</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">hosted by NHS Health </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Scotland;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> it is </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">open to everyone in Scotland who has a professional interest and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">significant involvement in the wider health improvement agenda including staff from the NHS, local authorities, academia and others.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  The aims of ScotPHN are:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">To undertake prioritised national pieces of work where there is a clearly identified need.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">To fac</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ilitate information exchange between public health practitioners, link with other networks and share learning.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">To create effective communication amongst professionals and the public to allow efficient co-ordination of public health activity.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">•</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">To support a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nd enhance the capabilities and functionality of the Scottish Directors of Public Health Group.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35pt; text-indent:-35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">1.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">NHS Health Scotland is a Special Health Board in NHS Scotland whose work focuses on:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Linking together experts from across Scotland to tackle the biggest i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ssues in achieving the right to good health</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Compiling world class evidence and research to further Scotland’s understanding of health inequalities</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Influencing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> policy makers at all levels to design targeted interventions to help build a fairer healthier Scotland</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Impact on social sector housing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">in Scotland</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">At the end of May 2013, the Scottish Government and C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">onvention of Scottish Local Authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> carrie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">d out a survey of all </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cottish local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to gain an early understanding of the impact of under occupancy </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">measures</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  With a 94% response rate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, it was </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">estimated that: -</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">82,500 households</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in Scotland </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">were </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">incurring a reduction in their housing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">benefit because they were assessed as under occupying their property.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-indent:35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Of these households:-</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Around</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">68,500 were under-occupying by one bedroom.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Around</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">14,000 were under-occupying by two or more bedrooms</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Around</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">47,500 were local authority tenants.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Around</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">35</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,000 were housing association tenants</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35pt; text-indent:-35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35pt; text-indent:-35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The average reduction is estimated to be around £11 per week per household and if households were to take no mitigating action, this would result in an estimated total reduction in Housing Benefit payments to Sco</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tland of around £50 million per annum.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35pt; text-indent:-35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35pt; text-indent:-35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Around 80% of household</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> affected by the under-occupancy penalty i.e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> around 63,500 households are estimated to contain an adult with a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">disability recognised under the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Disability Discrimination Act.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  And, a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">round </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">15,500 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">households affected by the under-occupancy penalty are estimated to be families with children.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35pt; text-indent:-35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35pt; text-indent:-35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Of the 82,500 households affected, 60,000 would need to move to a one bedroom property to avoid under occupation penalties.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> However it </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is estimat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> that only around 20,000 one bedroom local authority or housing association properties become available for letting each year.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35pt; text-indent:-35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35pt; text-indent:-35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">With the exception of one, all local authorities with housing stock reported an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">increase in arrears due to under occupan</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cy. Three quarters of councils are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">reporting that non-payment of rent following </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">under occupancy changes is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">directly responsible for the increase in their rent arrears.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Of that rent now due to be collected from tenants affected by under occupancy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">measu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">res, 60% of councils are reported receiving 40% or less and 80% reported</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">receiving 50% or less as at the end of May</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35pt; text-indent:-35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35pt; text-indent:-35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">2.6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In total, councils have received over 22,000 applications for DHPs since advising</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">tenants of revised Housing Benefit awards. For 19 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">local authorities this is 4 times</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">higher than the same period last year.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Impact of debt on health</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Given the increase in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">rent </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">arrears due to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">under occupancy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, there are clearly a significant nu</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ber of tenants who are now in debt in Scotland.  The </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">lationship between the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">impact of debt on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">health</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and in particular mental health</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is well </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">established</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The under occupancy rules </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">disproportionately</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> affect people who are already disadvantaged, including disabled people and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">those</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> who suffer long term health conditions, addictions, mental health problems and carers.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35pt; text-indent:-35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Being in debt can</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">negatively affect a person’s mental health, while</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">living with a mental health problem increases the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">likelihood of falling into debt</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">for example</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the number of people </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">who have trouble paying their debts are more than twice as likely to have mental health problems or suffer severe anxiety compared with the general population</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35pt; text-indent:-35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 35pt; text-indent:-35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">3.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">According to the Royal College of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Psychiatrists</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ore debt equate</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s to more mental ill health, even after adjustment for income and other socio-demographic variables.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  Their research has concluded that:</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Half of all people with debt in the general population have a mental disorder, compared to 14% of people with no debts, and 15% of the general population. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">People with more than 5 separate debts have on average a 6-fold increase in mental disorder.  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Utili</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ty disconnection and cutting down on utility usage are associated with 3-4 times and twice the average rates of mental disorder respectively. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eople in fuel poverty were over 4 times more likely to suffer anxiety or depression than people who could pay th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">eir fuel bills easily. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Change in financial status is associated with suicidal ideation and difficulty repaying debt is a risk factor for suicide. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Although both low income and debt are associated with mental illness, the effect of income on mental health </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">appears to be mediated by debt.  </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Impact of homelessness on health</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In contra</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t to England, homelessness has been falling in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cot</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  However the increase in rent arrears due to under </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">occupancy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> rules and lack of appropriate housing stock for people to ‘downsize’ </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> is likely to increase evictions. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Whilst some local authorities in Scotland have stated they will not evict tenants who fall into arrears </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">because</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of the under-occupancy rules, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">most hou</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">sing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> associations and local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">authorities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cannot</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> afford to take th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> approach</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, therefore</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> it is likely that t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">here will be an increase in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">number of people who become homeless</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Poor health is a well established consequence of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">homelessness</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> this can include </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">chronic conditions as well as anxiety, stress, self-harm, other mental health problems and infectious diseases. A significant minority of homeless people are dependent on drugs or alcohol often alongside mental health problems and other m</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ultiple needs</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">An increase in h</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ealth problems </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> not confined to those sleeping rough. People living in temporary accommodation, with friends or in hostels have little stability, often have to share kitchens and bathrooms and have little privacy or security</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. They may also experience problems relating t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">o damp or overcrowded conditions. Research also shows that homeless families in rural areas may spend longer in temporary accommodation than those in urban areas</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and that</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> health problems arising from such circumstances include an increased risk of dermato</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">logical problems, musculoskeletal problems, poor obstetric outcomes and a range of mental health problems.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The effect on children in homeless families living in temporary accommodation can be serious</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. There are many detrimental effects on the physi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cal and emotional development of children living in unsettled or overcrowded accommodation with little room to play or do homework. Studies have shown children in these circumstances </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are more likely to experience</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> behavioural disturbance, have higher levels of illness and infection, have poor sleep patterns and are more prone to accidental injury</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">4.5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It can be more difficult for homeless people to sustain continuity of care, to meet appointments made a long time </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">in advance, or to participate in health </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">improvement and health promotion activities, such as healthy eating and physical activity</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> Impact </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">of low</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">income on health</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Whilst </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">some tenants </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">may become homeless because they have incurred arrears due to the under </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">occupancy</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> rules; other tenants on low incomes, with no option of moving to a smaller property, will try to meet the shortfall in rent, therefore having less money to spend on basic liv</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ing costs such as fuel, food and transport.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The rapid increase in the number of Food Banks now available in Scotland </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">serve</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to illustrate a growing level of need that individuals and families face as a result of increasing financial difficulties</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Any</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> decrease in income for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ose</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> population groups </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">affected by the under occupancy rules is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> likely to cause increased income inequalities in Scotland, increased fuel poverty, increased food poverty (and a consequent shift from quality foodstuffs to calorific quantity); and decreased housing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">security</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  These factors are likely to cause a number </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">of negative health outcomes, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">and predictions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">: </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">increased cardiovascular and respiratory illness  </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">increases in obesity-related illnesses </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">worse mental health and general wellbeing</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">increases in avoidable winter mortality</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">increased substance misuse and a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ssociated alcohol- and drug-related harms</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">increased unprotected sex and associated rises in sexually transmitted infections </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">increased health inequalities</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.35pt; text-indent:-28.35pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">5.4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Those population groups who</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">se health is most </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">likely to be most affected </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> disabled people, carers and women, and those living in rural communities in Scotland</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Prior to April 2013, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">th</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ese</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> population group</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> were already </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">found to be </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">disproportionably</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> affected by the recent recession and public sector adjustments. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Scottish Gover</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">nment Social Research</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in 2010</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">found that:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">People in debt and facing unemployment are known to suffer higher rates of mental illness, unhappiness, separations and divorce</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">With tighter domestic budgets, victims of domestic abuse may feel unable to leave an </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">abusive partner</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Families with disabled children with lower incomes and higher costs will feel increased pressure if there are cuts to social work services and respite care and this will put additional pressure on family relationships and health</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The cuts to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> social work services may mean that carers will have to do more than they should or are able to</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Any reduction or freeze on benefit levels will not reflect increased costs of food and fuel meaning that there is less money for the purchase of essential items</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Rural dwellers and older people are facing difficulties with meeting fuel costs over harsh winters leading to increased cold weather related deaths</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The total number of disconnections from the power supply masks the actual number of people living without </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">power at certain times: if people cannot afford a power card for their meter they can be without power for prolonged periods and this is not recorded</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Disabled people, the low skilled and young unemployed have experienced a more substantive setback in the r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ecession, and carry fewer ‘protective factors’ into the f</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">uture </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Recent increases in food costs (+30%) have led to more people buying cheaper ranges of products from low cost shops with consequent impacts on nutritional status, obesity and dental health. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Impact on NHS services</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.1</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The potential increase in the burden of ill health due to increase in</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">health inequalities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">income inequalities</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">poverty and debt </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">will clearly have an impact on NHS services, particularly primary care</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in terms of increasing demand for appointments and increased costs associated with diagnostic testing and medication</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  And</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> what is of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">particular </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">concern </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">the increasing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> demand</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for medical evidence to support applications for Discretionary Housing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Payment (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">DHP)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Given that 80% of those affected by the under-occupancy rules in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Scotland</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> are disabled, many are applying for DHP on medical</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">or health grounds.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Due to a lack of clear guidance</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> and supported by Local Medical Committees</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">, GP’s are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">taking a number of approaches in </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">responding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> to reques</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">s for medical evidence to support applications for DHP, this includes charging for the evidence or refusing to provide any evidence.  GP’s have taken this stance given the number of r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">quests they now re</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ceive to provide medical evidence in support of those appealing W</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ork Capability </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ssessment (WCA)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">decisions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">6.3</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">he additional work of providing evidence for DHP applications and WCA appeals falls disproportionately on general practices in areas of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">deprivation in Scotland which are already struggling as a result of the inverse care law</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">7.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">onclusion</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">As outlined above </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">there are concerns amongst the NHS and public health </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">workforce</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> of the impact that the social size criteria is having on</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> the most vulnerable communities in Scotland.  Of the 82,500 households affected by the under occupancy rules, 60,000 need a one bedroom property, however only around 20,000 one bedroom </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">properties</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> in the social housing sector become available each year.  C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">onsequently the impact o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">f the under occupancy rules are </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">likely to cause an increase in health problems, health inequalities and pressure on NHS services, particularly primary care.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">It is hoped that the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">UK </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Parliament Work and Pensions C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">ommittee</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> recognise these impacts and can identify how these impacts can be minimise in order to protect the health of those </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">most </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">affected in Scotland.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">20 September 2013</span><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Bilbliography</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">In </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">addition to the references in the footnotes, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">evidence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> for this report </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">has been </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">drawn</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt"> from a number of published and unpublished documents – see below.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">The impact of the economic downturn and policy changes on health inequalities in London; University College London, Institute of Health Equity (2012)</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">GP’s at the Deep End Austerity Report </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">(2012)</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Interim Guidance for NHS Boards; Scottish Public Health Network (2012)</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Welfare Reform and older people in Scotland; agescotland (2013)</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Voices from the Frontline: Sanctions; Citizens Advice Scotland (2012)</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Monitoring poverty and social exclusion in S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cotland: Joseph Rowntree Foundation (2013)</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Literature review of the health impacts of welfare reform; NHS Highland (2012)</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Rapid equality and human rights impact assessment; Scottish Health Impact Assessment Network, unpublished (2012)</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 33.01pt; padding-left:2.99pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">Unpublished evidence </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">from S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt">cottish Council for Voluntary Organisations (2012)</span></li><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font